{"source_key":"sha256-45386b662710fcb79bc6648cdf109f71","record_index":11,"record_hash":"sha256:1ba3376579fcf3e9d598724b1b31f6ea05bd3b0788c2c341bdd5e18029e3f1cd","timestamp":"2026-06-03T08:48:30.201Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"claude:user:tool_result","role":null,"text":"{\"additions\":302,\"author\":{\"id\":\"MDQ6VXNlcjk0MTc1MzE=\",\"is_bot\":false,\"login\":\"Andrej730\",\"name\":\"Andrej730\"},\"baseRefName\":\"master\",\"body\":\"Resolves issue mentioned in https://github.[REDACTED:entropy].\\r\\n\\r\\nThe original issue is that Ubuntu 26.04 LTS now has a new default terminal emulator, `ptyxis`, superseding `gnome-terminal`. I've added support for `ptyxis` in general in a separate PR (https://github.[REDACTED:entropy]), but it still means that new users from 26.04 won't have \\\"open in termal\\\" working out-of-the-box.\\r\\n\\r\\nSo basic options were to either switch to ptyxis now or somehow detect Ubuntu 25.10+, when it was added. Both have significant downsides - there are still a lot of users on 24.04 and other distros and hardcoding logic seems fragile.\\r\\n\\r\\nAs a general solution, I thought we can just consider all supported terminals, when trying to figure what's to use as the default for the current user.\\r\\nSo I moved `defaultTerminalForPlatform` from frontend to backend so we can run `which` on all terminals we do support and subsequnetly `allTerminalOptions` now also comes from Rust. Tested - works fine, no errors.\\r\\nOne special case in `get_recommended_terminal_for_platform` - we don't check anything using `which` and just use `terminal`, as it's generally available on every Mac and is the system default there.\\r\\n\",\"deletions\":106,\"files\":[{\"path\":\"apps/desktop/README.md\",\"additions\":11,\"deletions\":5},{\"path\":\"apps/desktop/src/components/settings/GeneralSettings.svelte\",\"additions\":18,\"deletions\":32},{\"path\":\"apps/desktop/src/lib/bootstrap/deps.ts\",\"additions\":3,\"deletions\":0},{\"path\":\"ap